# Commenting & JSDoc Rule

When you **add or change code**, you must **add/update comments** so they stay correct.

- **Prefer docblocks over inline comments**:
  - TypeScript/JS: use **JSDoc** `/** ... */` for every new/changed function, method, class, exported type, and any non-trivial private helper.
  - Keep docblocks **intent/contract focused**: what it does, why it exists, constraints, side effects, invariants, failure modes.
- **Inline `//` comments only when needed**:
  - Use them for **non-obvious logic** (DOM quirks, flaky behavior workarounds, regex parsing, timezones/business rules).
  - Avoid line-by-line narration of obvious code.
- **Update comments when behavior changes**:
  - If code changes meaning/assumptions, update the comment in the same edit.
  - If you can’t keep an existing comment accurate, **remove or rewrite it**.

## Examples (TypeScript)

```ts
/** Downloads the CSV export and returns the local temp file path Playwright saved. */
async downloadTableCsv(): Promise<string> { /* ... */ }
```

```ts
// Tabs can leave non-visible duplicates in the DOM; only use a visible label.
const candidates = page.getByText(/Data as of\\s+\\d{1,2}\\/\\d{1,2}\\/\\d{4}/);
```
